    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Filago perpusilla improperly are experiencing allergic reactions, as it contains sesquiterpene lactones and other bioactive compounds, which can trigger an allergic response in sensitive individuals. Inducing allergic reactions in others is also a concern, as the plant's allergenic potential is not limited to those who come into contact with it. Triggering asthma attacks is a possible side effect, as the plant's allergenic compounds can exacerbate respiratory issues in individuals with pre-existing conditions. Developing skin irritation is another potential side effect, as the plant's sap can cause skin redness, itching, and inflammation in some individuals. Inducing skin irritation in others is also possible, as the plant's bioactive compounds can cause an immune response that leads to skin inflammation and discomfort.",
    "uses": "Filago perpusilla is a species of flowering plant in the family Asteraceae, commonly known as the lesser cusan or lesser cudweed. Filago perpusilla has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes, including treating digestive issues, skin problems, and respiratory issues. Its leaves and flowers are rich in antioxidants and have anti-inflammatory properties. In traditional folk medicine, Filago perpusilla is often used to treat conditions such as fever, cough, and sore throats. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Filago perpusilla as a medicinal treatment.",
    "taxonomy": "Filago perpusilla is classified as a species of flowering plant in the family Compositae, more commonly known as the Asteraceae family. This family consists of daisies and sunflowers, among other species. Filago perpusilla is further classified as a member of the genus Filago, which is a group of small, annual plants. The plant's classification is as follows: Kingdom: Plantae, Phylum: Magnoliophyta, Class: Magnoliopsida, Order: Asterales, Family: Asteraceae, Genus: Filago, Species: F. perpusilla. This classification helps to identify and distinguish Filago perpusilla from other plant species.",
    "benefits": "Filago perpusilla, a species of fleabane, is believed to have various health benefits due to its rich content of flavonoids, phenolic acids, and other bioactive compounds. The plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine to treat various ailments, including fever, cough, and respiratory issues. Its leaves and flowers are said to possess anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may help protect against oxidative stress and cell damage. Additionally, the plant's bioactive compounds may have antimicrobial and antiviral effects, helping to prevent infections and promote wound healing. Further research is needed to confirm the full extent of Filago perpusilla's health benefits and potential applications.",
    "parts": "Filago perpusilla, also known as lesser cudweed, is a plant species that has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. The medicinal parts of Filago perpusilla are primarily its leaves and flowers, which are rich in antioxidants and have anti-inflammatory properties. The plant is used to treat various ailments, including skin conditions, respiratory issues, and gastrointestinal problems. Its leaves and flowers are typically used in infusions or as a topical application. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and uses of Filago perpusilla.",
    "intro": "Filago perpusilla, also known as small cudweed, is a small annual herbaceous plant belonging to the family Asteraceae. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, with reported health benefits including the reduction of inflammation and improvement of respiratory issues, such as bronchitis and asthma, due to its expectorant and anti-inflammatory effects. Bioactive constituents of Filago perpusilla include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and essential oils, which are responsible for its therapeutic properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Filago perpusilla is often used to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are commonly used to alleviate respiratory problems and promote overall well-being."
